        <item>
        <title>Quest 3 on Arch</title>
        <link>https://saipheblue.github.io/p/quest-3-on-arch/</link>
        <pubDate>Mon, 30 Dec 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
        
        <guid>https://saipheblue.github.io/p/quest-3-on-arch/</guid>
        <description>&lt;img src="https://saipheblue.github.io/p/quest-3-on-arch/3.jpg" alt="Featured image of post Quest 3 on Arch" /&gt;&lt;p&gt;There are plenty of guides online on how to set everything up on Windows, but not so many for Arch Linux or Linux in general.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;steamvr&#34;&gt;SteamVR
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;SteamVR is the backbone of PC VR gaming, supporting a wide range of headsets and offering access to countless VR titles.
It is part of your Steam library—just download and run it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you&amp;rsquo;ve previously used your headset on Windows, you might encounter an issue with Steam Link on Linux. It displays the error:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;&#39;Streaming VR is not available from that computer.&#39;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Due to this limitation, we need to use alternative software to pair with SteamVR.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://saipheblue.github.io/p/quest-3-on-arch/1.png&#34;
	width=&#34;1743&#34;
	height=&#34;405&#34;
	srcset=&#34;https://saipheblue.github.io/p/quest-3-on-arch/1_hu1533604363331417481.png 480w, https://saipheblue.github.io/p/quest-3-on-arch/1_hu4519556953867718277.png 1024w&#34;
	loading=&#34;lazy&#34;
	
	
		class=&#34;gallery-image&#34; 
		data-flex-grow=&#34;430&#34;
		data-flex-basis=&#34;1032px&#34;
	
&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;sidequest&#34;&gt;SideQuest
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;SideQuest is a popular platform for sideloading apps, games, and experimental software onto standalone VR headsets. It expands the possibilities of your VR device beyond the default app store.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Visit the official &lt;a class=&#34;link&#34; href=&#34;https://sidequestvr.com/&#34;  target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;
    &gt;SideQuest site&lt;/a&gt; for a detailed guide on how to connect your headset, enable developer mode, and install all prerequisites.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you&amp;rsquo;re having trouble connecting your headset, ensure you have ADB (Android Debug Bridge) installed. To check, run:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;
&lt;table class=&#34;lntable&#34;&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;1
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-fallback&#34; data-lang=&#34;fallback&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;adb version
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;If it’s not installed, you can get it with:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;
&lt;table class=&#34;lntable&#34;&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;1
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-gdscript3&#34; data-lang=&#34;gdscript3&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;n&#34;&gt;sudo&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&#34;n&#34;&gt;pacman&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&#34;o&#34;&gt;-&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;n&#34;&gt;S&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&#34;n&#34;&gt;android&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;o&#34;&gt;-&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;n&#34;&gt;tools&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;h2 id=&#34;alvr-air-light-vr&#34;&gt;ALVR (Air Light VR)
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://saipheblue.github.io/p/quest-3-on-arch/2.png&#34;
	width=&#34;2549&#34;
	height=&#34;492&#34;
	srcset=&#34;https://saipheblue.github.io/p/quest-3-on-arch/2_hu474655151797802696.png 480w, https://saipheblue.github.io/p/quest-3-on-arch/2_hu6650122288950677746.png 1024w&#34;
	loading=&#34;lazy&#34;
	
	
		class=&#34;gallery-image&#34; 
		data-flex-grow=&#34;518&#34;
		data-flex-basis=&#34;1243px&#34;
	
&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;ALVR allows wireless PC VR gaming by streaming games from your PC to a standalone headset like the Meta Quest series. It uses low-latency video encoding to provide a seamless experience.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Download ALVR from the official &lt;a class=&#34;link&#34; href=&#34;https://github.com/alvr-org/ALVR/releases&#34;  target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;
    &gt;ALVR GitHub releases page&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Install the APK on your headset using SideQuest.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Extract the &lt;code&gt;.tar&lt;/code&gt; file on your Arch Linux machine and run the executable.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://saipheblue.github.io/p/quest-3-on-arch/4.png&#34;
	width=&#34;2559&#34;
	height=&#34;1348&#34;
	srcset=&#34;https://saipheblue.github.io/p/quest-3-on-arch/4_hu5291950623060969288.png 480w, https://saipheblue.github.io/p/quest-3-on-arch/4_hu9895093760156796286.png 1024w&#34;
	loading=&#34;lazy&#34;
	
	
		class=&#34;gallery-image&#34; 
		data-flex-grow=&#34;189&#34;
		data-flex-basis=&#34;455px&#34;
	
&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Follow the on-screen instructions to set up ALVR. Be sure to mark the headset as &amp;ldquo;trusted.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Once done, start SteamVR.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;From there, &lt;b&gt;manually start&lt;/b&gt; VR games from your PC. While this is a limitation, once the game is running, you can enjoy your session in the VR headset.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;tips--tricks&#34;&gt;Tips &amp;amp; tricks
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;h3 id=&#34;fix-for-black-screen-on-headset&#34;&gt;Fix for Black Screen on Headset
&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;If your VR game runs on your PC but your headset displays a black screen, try this fix:
Add the following command to SteamVR&amp;rsquo;s launch options:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;~/.local/share/Steam/steamapps/common/SteamVR/bin/vrmonitor.sh %command%&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;(Note: File paths may vary depending on where you installed SteamVR.)&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;fix-for-games-not-launching-in-vr-mode&#34;&gt;Fix for Games Not Launching in VR Mode
&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Is the game not launching in VR mode? Go to the game properties, then to Compatibility, and enable Proton. After that, in General settings or during the first game launch, it will ask if you want to play in normal mode or VR mode.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;happy-gaming--&#34;&gt;Happy gaming ! :)
&lt;/h2&gt;</description>
        </item>
        <item>
        <title>DIY Geiger counter</title>
        <link>https://saipheblue.github.io/p/diy-geiger-counter/</link>
        <pubDate>Thu, 26 Dec 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
        
        <guid>https://saipheblue.github.io/p/diy-geiger-counter/</guid>
        <description>&lt;img src="https://saipheblue.github.io/p/diy-geiger-counter/5.jpg" alt="Featured image of post DIY Geiger counter" /&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://saipheblue.github.io/p/diy-geiger-counter/2.png&#34;
	width=&#34;1911&#34;
	height=&#34;1086&#34;
	srcset=&#34;https://saipheblue.github.io/p/diy-geiger-counter/2_hu5362382509408535200.png 480w, https://saipheblue.github.io/p/diy-geiger-counter/2_hu8486877396199715324.png 1024w&#34;
	loading=&#34;lazy&#34;
	
	
		class=&#34;gallery-image&#34; 
		data-flex-grow=&#34;175&#34;
		data-flex-basis=&#34;422px&#34;
	
&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://saipheblue.github.io/p/diy-geiger-counter/1.jpg&#34;
	width=&#34;4000&#34;
	height=&#34;3000&#34;
	srcset=&#34;https://saipheblue.github.io/p/diy-geiger-counter/1_hu11219505733991928216.jpg 480w, https://saipheblue.github.io/p/diy-geiger-counter/1_hu4261674103906523970.jpg 1024w&#34;
	loading=&#34;lazy&#34;
	
	
		class=&#34;gallery-image&#34; 
		data-flex-grow=&#34;133&#34;
		data-flex-basis=&#34;320px&#34;
	
&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;what-will-you-need&#34;&gt;What will you need
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Geiger–Müller kit &lt;a class=&#34;link&#34; href=&#34;https://www.ebay.com/itm/396034408437?_skw=Geiger_Counter_RadiationD-v1.1-CAJOE&#34;  target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;
    &gt;for example this one&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Raspberry pi - any model is fine but guide is written for raspberry pi 5. For older models you will need to make some adjustments&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;hardware&#34;&gt;Hardware
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Connect 5V to any 5V, Ground to any ground and VIN to GPIO4 (pin 7)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;rpi5-gpio-diagram&#34;&gt;Rpi5 GPIO diagram
&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://saipheblue.github.io/p/diy-geiger-counter/4.png&#34;
	width=&#34;2165&#34;
	height=&#34;1247&#34;
	srcset=&#34;https://saipheblue.github.io/p/diy-geiger-counter/4_hu14689943616109472642.png 480w, https://saipheblue.github.io/p/diy-geiger-counter/4_hu17050551416226961946.png 1024w&#34;
	loading=&#34;lazy&#34;
	
	
		class=&#34;gallery-image&#34; 
		data-flex-grow=&#34;173&#34;
		data-flex-basis=&#34;416px&#34;
	
&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;μsvh-ratio&#34;&gt;μSv/h Ratio
&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Check the tube that is installed in your kit. In my case, I have J305. We need to calculate μSv/h ratio based on the tube&amp;rsquo;s sensitivity.
For J305, almost everyone is using the wrong coefficient/ratio of 0.00812037037037. Here is the formula I used, together with a source elaborating why 0.0081 is wrong: J305 has 25 CPM 1 / (25 * 60 / 8.77)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;link&#34; href=&#34;https://medium.com/@iotdevices/geiger-tube-j305-how-to-calculate-the-conversion-factor-of-cpm-to-%CE%BCsv-h-technical-note-b0cc14850576&#34;  target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;
    &gt;Source&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;software&#34;&gt;Software
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;I am using Raspbian OS. If you have a different OS, commands may differ.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;required-files&#34;&gt;Required files
&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Navigate to &lt;b&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;link&#34; href=&#34;https://github.com/saipheblue/Rpi5_Geiger_Counter_RadiationD-v1.1-CAJOE?search=1&#34;  target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;
    &gt;this&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/b&gt; repository and clone it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In documentation folder, you can find more detailed information about how everything works and values used in calculations&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;issues--pre-req&#34;&gt;Issues &amp;amp; pre-req
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;h3 id=&#34;install-flask&#34;&gt;Install flask
&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;
&lt;table class=&#34;lntable&#34;&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;1
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-fallback&#34; data-lang=&#34;fallback&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;pip install flask
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;If you got permisisons error, use sudo&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you get a 404 error, make sure index page is in the &amp;ldquo;templates&amp;rdquo; folder. It is case sensitive. The structure should be as follows:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;Project
    geiger.py
    templates
        index.html
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;m4011-tube&#34;&gt;M4011 tube
&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;The manufacturer’s documentation lists the M4011, which has the same specs as the J305.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;ssl&#34;&gt;SSL
&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;ssl_context=(&amp;lsquo;cert.pem&amp;rsquo;, &amp;lsquo;key.pem&amp;rsquo;) can be replaced by ssl_context=&amp;lsquo;adhoc&amp;rsquo; if you dont have the keys&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;link&#34; href=&#34;https://zhangtemplar.github.io/flask/&#34;  target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;
    &gt;Source&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;gpio-problem&#34;&gt;GPIO problem
&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;RPi 5 has issues with GPIO. Remove the current GPIO library using:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;
&lt;table class=&#34;lntable&#34;&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;1
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-fallback&#34; data-lang=&#34;fallback&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;sudo apt remove python3-rpi.gpio
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Then install lgpio:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;
&lt;table class=&#34;lntable&#34;&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;1
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-fallback&#34; data-lang=&#34;fallback&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;python3 -m pip install rpi-lgpio flask
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;If you have installation problems, use this (but it could break system packages, or you can use a virtual environment):&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;
&lt;table class=&#34;lntable&#34;&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;1
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-fallback&#34; data-lang=&#34;fallback&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;python3 -m pip install rpi-lgpio flask --break-system-packages
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;link&#34; href=&#34;https://pimylifeup.com/python-externally-managed-environment/&#34;  target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;
    &gt;more info&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;run-the-script&#34;&gt;Run the script
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Simply run &lt;b&gt;geiger.py&lt;/b&gt; to start measuring:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;
&lt;table class=&#34;lntable&#34;&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;1
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-fallback&#34; data-lang=&#34;fallback&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;python3 geiger.py
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Then navigate to &lt;b&gt;127.0.0.1:80/index&lt;/b&gt; to see the chart&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
        </item>
        <item>
        <title>Colorize and List IPs</title>
        <link>https://saipheblue.github.io/p/colorize-and-list-ips/</link>
        <pubDate>Thu, 19 Dec 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
        
        <guid>https://saipheblue.github.io/p/colorize-and-list-ips/</guid>
        <description>&lt;img src="https://saipheblue.github.io/p/colorize-and-list-ips/1.png" alt="Featured image of post Colorize and List IPs" /&gt;&lt;p&gt;Did you know you can colorize and print all IP addresses and interfaces on Linux in a tabular format for better readability?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The syntax is:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;
&lt;table class=&#34;lntable&#34;&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;1
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;2
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-fallback&#34; data-lang=&#34;fallback&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;ip -br -c addr show
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;ip -br -c link show
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;link&#34; href=&#34;https://mastodon.social/@nixCraft/113679576456152013&#34;  target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;
    &gt;Source&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
        </item>
